Exploring the seasonal dynamics of ozone in New York (1973)

In this exercise, I explore the seasonal variability of ozone concentration in New York during the months of May to September 1973, using the built-in R dataset airquality. The dataset comes from the New York State Department of Conservation and contains daily air quality measurements collected in New York City. The target variable is ozone, which I investigate in relation to meteorological variables such as solar radiation, wind speed, and maximum air temperature. These variables provide the basis to address the following question:

How do meteorological conditions and seasonal patterns influence daily ozone concentration in New York during the summer of 1973?

Data description

The airquality dataset consists of daily measurements from May to September 1973, and include different variables (Table 1). Due to these variables are in unit that not belong to SI units, I transformed them into SI units to enhance clarity and interpretation. I also checked the dataset for missing values. Ozone and Solar.R contain some missing entries, which were handled appropriately (complete case analysis) during the analysis to avoid distortion of statistical results.

Variable Description Units (original) Units (converted)
Ozone Mean ozone in parts per billion (ppb) ppb μg/m³ (1 ppb = 1.96 μg/m³)
Solar.R Solar radiation Langley/day MJ/m²/day (1 Langley = 0.04184 MJ)
Wind Wind speed miles per hour (mph) meters per second (m/s)
Temp Maximum daily temperature degrees Fahrenheit (°F) degrees Celsius (°C)
Month Month (1–12) - -
Day Day of the month - -
Table 1. Description of the airquality dataset: variable name, original units, and converted units.

Ozone levels show substantial day-to-day variability, as indicated by
the relatively high standard deviation. This suggests that ozone
concentration is sensitive to changing daily conditions. Additionally,
the presence of extreme values points to potential ozone spikes, likely
outliers, — which may be linked to specific weather events or unusual
combinations of meteorological variables. Solar.R also varies
considerably, with some days recording values near zero, likely
corresponding to fully overcast or rainy days. In contrast, Wind
displays relatively low variability, suggesting more stable wind
conditions throughout the summer months. Finally, Temp seems to falls
within the expected range for summer in New York.






Seasonal patterns


To explore how ozone and related meteorological variables vary over
the summer months, I created boxplots grouped by month (from May to
September) for Ozone and meteorological variables. These plots help
reveal seasonal trends, variability, and potential outliers.


The boxplots by month reveal clear seasonal patterns (Table 2): Mean
Ozone levels rise from May, peak in July, and decline through September,
following the variability of increasing Temp and Solar.R. August shows
the greatest variability, indicating more frequent spikes but also
others present in May and September. Temp steadily increases until July,
then decline, while Solar.R follows a similar curve but less obvious and
with higher variability. Wind remains relatively stable but slightly
lower in midsummer, which may contribute to ozone accumulation. These
patterns suggest that warmer, sunnier, and less windy conditions in
midsummer promote higher Ozone concentrations.




Figure 1. Monthly variability of daily Ozone and meteorological
variables from May (5) to September (9) of 1973. Value units are the
same as in Table 2.








Relationship of Ozone and meteorological variables


To better understand how each meteorological variable influences
Ozone concentration, I created scatterplots with linear regression
lines. These plots help visualize the direction and strength of the
relationships between Ozone and Temp, Wind, and Solar.R.


Ozone shows a strong positive correlation with Temp (Figure 2),
indicating that higher temperatures are associated with increased ozone
levels, likely due to enhanced photochemical activity. In contrast,
ozone has a negative relationship with Wind, suggesting that stronger
winds help disperse ozone and reduce its concentration (Figure 3). The
relationship between Ozone and Solar.R is moderately positive but more
scattered, possibly due unmeasured factors influencing ozone formation
(Figure 4). Overall, these patterns support the idea that heat and
sunlight drive ozone production, while wind acts as a dispersing
force.

both variables. Liner regression model and Pearson correlation are also

Temporal variability of Ozone and meteorological variables


To observe how ozone levels changed over time, I plotted a time
series of daily Ozone together with the meteorological variables. The
plot shows a clear seasonal trend, with Ozone gradually increasing
through June and peaking in mid to late July, before declining toward
September. Short-term fluctuations are also visible, reflecting
day-to-day variability driven by changing weather conditions as seen by
Temp, Wind and Solar.R. This pattern supports the idea that Ozone is
influenced by both seasonal and transient meteorological factors.




Figure 5. Daily series of Ozone and meteorological variables during
the summer of 1973. Value units are the same as in Table 2.









Summary


The analysis reveals that Ozone concentration in New York during the
summer of 1973 was significantly influenced by temperature and wind,
with higher temperatures associated with increased ozone levels and
stronger winds linked to lower concentrations due to pollutant
dispersion. While solar radiation showed a positive relationship with
ozone, this correlation was moderate and weaker than expected based on
previous research (Yang et al., 2024), which typically finds a stronger
link. Seasonal patterns revealed that ozone peaked in midsummer,
coinciding with the warmest and sunniest periods. Overall, these results
suggest that although temperature and wind play major roles in ozone
variability, the influence of solar radiation in this dataset was
curiously less pronounced, highlighting potential data limitations or
other influencing factors. More data is needed to explore these
outcomes.
